                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/952: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-04-13T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 13, 1926—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>80. Your 162, April 3, 2 p.m. While inclined to agree with you that present arms
                    embargo has failed materially to restrict the supply of arms to warring factions
                    in China, the Department does not believe that the United States should take the
                    lead in recommending its revision or discontinuance, especially at the present
                    time when to do so would offer seeming justification for a charge that we
                    desired to favor one faction against another. The Department would therefor
                    prefer that you refrain for the present from initiating any discussion of
                    question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
